\section{Software architecture}

% note that libc should be thread-safe, malloc use locks!

% take common.ml structure for the TOC of this document?

%claude:
Unlike a compiler or a build system, a library is not a pipeline.
It is a collection of largely independent components that programs
link against and call as needed. The ``architecture'' of a C
library is therefore better understood as a layering:
%
\begin{enumerate}
\item {\em System call wrappers} (in [[9sys/]] and [[9syscall/]])
provide thin assembly stubs that trap into the kernel for
[[open]], [[read]], [[write]], [[rfork]], [[exec]], [[brk]],
[[rendezvous]], etc.

\item {\em Core services} built on those system calls:
the memory allocator ([[malloc]]/[[free]] on top of [[sbrk]]),
buffered I/O ([[Biobuf]] on top of [[read]]/[[write]]),
formatted output ([[print]] on top of [[write]]),
locking ([[qlock]] on top of [[rendezvous]]),
and networking ([[dial]]/[[announce]] on top of [[open]]/[[read]]/[[write]]
to [[/net/]]).

\item {\em Pure computation}: string manipulation, math functions,
regular expressions, and 9P marshalling.
These do not use system calls at all---though they may
call [[malloc]], which itself may call the [[sbrk]] system
call to grow the heap.

\item {\em [[libthread]]}: a layer on top of everything else,
providing cooperative threads, channels, and IO procs. When
linked in, [[libthread]] replaces [[main]], [[exits]],
[[dial]], [[_assert]], and [[_sysfatal]] with thread-aware
versions.
\end{enumerate}
%
The key dependency is that nearly everything depends on the
memory allocator, and the allocator itself depends on locks.
In \plan, [[rfork(RFMEM)]] creates a new process that shares
its parent's memory---effectively a system-level thread.
Since two such processes can call [[malloc]] concurrently,
the allocator must be thread-safe (see the discussion of
thread safety versus reentrancy in the Principles section).
More generally, [[libc]] functions that use global state
(e.g., [[syslog]], [[atexit]]) protect it with locks, making
\plan's [[libc]] safe for use with shared-memory processes.
[[libthread]]'s channels add another layer, depending on
locks, atomic operations, and the [[rendezvous]] system call.

%yoann: maybe ASCII diagram with those layers?
%claude:
The following diagram summarizes this layering:
\begin{verbatim}
  +-----------------------------------------------------------+
  |  libthread: threads, channels, alt, IO procs              |
  |  (replaces main, exits, dial, _sysfatal when linked in)   |
  +------------------+----------------------------------------+
  |  Core services   |  Pure computation                      |
  |  malloc/free     |  strings, runes, UTF-8                 |
  |  Biobuf          |  regexp, math, compression             |
  |  print/fprint    |  9P marshalling                        |
  |  qlock, dial     |                                        |
  +------------------+----------------------------------------+
  |  System call wrappers (9sys/, 9syscall/)                   |
  |  open, read, write, rfork, exec, brk, rendezvous, ...     |
  +-----------------------------------------------------------+
  |  Kernel                                                    |
  +-----------------------------------------------------------+
\end{verbatim}

\section{Book structure}

%claude: %trans:
You now have enough background to understand the source code
of the \plan core libraries.
%toc:
The rest of the book is organized in five parts.
%
Part~I ({\em Foundations}) covers the bedrock:
the core types and data structures in Chapter~\ref{chap:core-ds},
the system call interface in Chapter~\ref{chap:user-kernel},
the C runtime entry point [[_main()]] in Chapter~\ref{chap:main},
memory management (Chapter~\ref{chap:memops} for low-level
operations, Chapter~\ref{chap:malloc} for the [[malloc]] allocator),
and formatted output in Chapter~\ref{chap:fmt} (the extensible
[[print]] family used everywhere, including the kernel).
%
Part~II ({\em Data Processing}) covers pure computation:
strings in Chapter~\ref{chap:strings} (C strings, runes, and UTF-8),
regular expressions in Chapter~\ref{chap:regexp},
mathematics in Chapter~\ref{chap:math},
and compression in Chapter~\ref{chap:compression}.
%
Part~III ({\em System Services}) covers the library functions
that wrap system calls, roughly one family per chapter:
file I/O in Chapter~\ref{chap:fileio},
buffered I/O in Chapter~\ref{chap:bufio},
directories in Chapter~\ref{chap:dirs},
namespace operations in Chapter~\ref{chap:namespace},
time in Chapter~\ref{chap:time},
process management in Chapter~\ref{chap:fork},
error management in Chapter~\ref{chap:errors},
and security in Chapter~\ref{chap:security}.
%
Part~IV ({\em Concurrency and Communication}) covers
synchronization and IPC:
locks and queuing locks in Chapter~\ref{chap:concurrency},
IPC mechanisms (notes, pipes, 9P) in Chapter~\ref{chap:ipc},
the cooperative thread scheduler and channels in
Chapter~\ref{chap:threads} (the largest chapter in the book),
and networking in Chapter~\ref{chap:network}.
%
Part~V ({\em Debugging and Profiling}) covers
the library support for the \plan debugging and profiling tools
in Chapters~\ref{chap:debugging} and~\ref{chap:profiling}.
%
Finally, Chapter~\ref{chap:conclusion} concludes and gives pointers
to other books in the \principia series.

%###############################################################################
\part{Foundations}
%###############################################################################

%claude:
This part covers the bedrock that everything else is built on:
the type system ([[u.h]] and [[libc.h]]), the C runtime entry
point ([[_main]]), the system call interface to the kernel,
memory management---from the raw [[sbrk]] system call
through the [[Pool]] allocator to [[malloc]]/[[free]]---and
formatted output (the extensible [[print]] family).

%******************************************************************************
\chapter{Core Types and Data Structures}
%******************************************************************************
\label{chap:core-ds}

%claude:
This chapter presents the fundamental type definitions from
[[u.h]] and [[libc.h]] that every \plan C program relies on.
These headers establish the vocabulary of types---from basic
integers and booleans to Unicode runes and file descriptors---that
the rest of the library builds upon.

\section{Basic types}

% void, int, double,
% pointer, void*!
% signed vs unsigned, different int size, etc.
% All defined in Compiler.nw but libcore define a few aliases in u.h.

%yoann: small paragraph intro
%claude:
C provides a few primitive types ([[int]], [[char]], [[double]],
pointers), but a standard library typically extends these with
aliases for portability, convenience, and clarity. This section
covers the type definitions in [[u.h]] and [[libc.h]]: booleans,
fixed-width integers, Unicode characters (runes), and
floating-point bit manipulation.

\subsection{Booleans}

%yoann: explain most C programmers abuse int for book, but modern C separate, so I the author extended plan9 libs with those types (not in original plan9). Might be part of c99?
%claude:
Traditional C has no boolean type---programmers use [[int]]
with 0 for false and non-zero for true. C99 introduced
\verb+_Bool+ (with \verb+<stdbool.h>+), and C23 made [[bool]]
a keyword. The original \plan libraries did not define a
boolean type, but the author added this [[typedef]] to
make function signatures more readable. Go, \plan's
spiritual successor, has a proper [[bool]] from the start.

<<type [[bool]]>>=
typedef int bool;
enum _bool {
  false = 0,
  true = 1
};
@
%pad: I added that. But Pike must agree because they have bools in Go.
% also C23 has bool too (finally)


\subsection{Integers}

%claude:
\plan defines shorthand aliases for unsigned types and
fixed-width integers. The aliases exist because C's standard
types have platform-dependent sizes: [[long]] is 32~bits
on 32-bit architectures but 64~bits on 64-bit architectures
under gcc/clang (the LP64 model), which is a perennial source
of porting bugs. The [[vlong]] type (``very long'') provides
a guaranteed 64-bit integer regardless of architecture. The
[[u8int]], [[u16int]], [[u32int]], [[u64int]] types provide
explicit widths, similar to C99's \verb+<stdint.h>+ types
but predating them.

<<type [[uxxx]]>>=
typedef unsigned short  ushort;
typedef unsigned char   uchar;
typedef unsigned long   ulong;
typedef unsigned int    uint;
@

<<type [[byte]]>>=
typedef uchar byte;
@
% and byte*


% TODO: like in Rust/Zig use u8/u32/u64, s8/s32/s64
<<type [[uxxxint]]>>=
typedef unsigned char u8int;
typedef unsigned short u16int;
typedef unsigned int    u32int;
typedef unsigned long long u64int;
@
% ok this deserves to be in arm/u.h

%yoann: say those types defined in arch/arm/u.h because u32int might be different typedef on amd64 arch (maybe give an example of difference)
%claude:
These typedefs live in [[arm/u.h]] (not [[libc.h]]) because
they are architecture-specific. The \plan C compiler keeps
[[long]] at 32~bits on all architectures, but when porting
to gcc/clang (as in plan9port or Goken), [[long]] becomes
64~bits on 64-bit hosts (the LP64 model). The explicit-width
types like [[u32int]] guarantee exactly 32~bits regardless
of compiler, avoiding subtle bugs when the same code is
compiled for different targets.

% vlong for very long
% Note that 'long' is misleading because 32bits on 32bits arch
% but 64bits on 64bits arch, which leads to lots of issues when porting
% C code to 64bits arch (see goken many tricky long->int32)
<<type [[xxxvlong]]>>=
typedef long long   vlong;
typedef unsigned long long uvlong;
@
% see vlrt.c and _addv(), _mulv(), ... functions
% vlong is actually quite tricky. See \book{Compiler}


% A few convenient aliases
<<type [[usize]]>>=
typedef unsigned long   usize;
@


\subsection{Floats}

%last:
% - https://essenceia.github.io/projects/floating_dragon/

%claude:
[[FPdbleword]] is a union that overlays a [[double]] with its
raw bit representation as two 32-bit words. This is essential
for the math library: functions like [<NaN()>], [<isNaN()>], and
[<isInf()>] need to inspect or construct the IEEE~754 bit pattern
directly (exponent, mantissa, sign) rather than treating the
value as a number.
An IEEE~754 double-precision float is laid out as follows:
\begin{verbatim}
  63  62       52 51                                           0
 +---+-----------+---------------------------------------------+
 | S | Exponent  |                  Mantissa                   |
 | 1 |  11 bits  |                  52 bits                    |
 +---+-----------+---------------------------------------------+
       \_ hi word (bits 32-63) _/ \_____ lo word (bits 0-31) _/
\end{verbatim}
%
The [[hi]] word of [[FPdbleword]] contains the sign bit,
the 11-bit exponent, and the upper 20~bits of the mantissa.
The [[lo]] word contains the lower 32~bits of the mantissa.


% in arm/u.h so probably arch specific
<<type [[FPdbleword]]>>=
union FPdbleword
{
    double  x;

    struct {    /* little endian */
        ulong lo;
        ulong hi;
    };
};
@

% also useful is union { double d; uint64 x}
% to display internal representation in hex of a double.

%claude:
Note the \verb+/* little endian */+ comment: [[lo]] comes
before [[hi]] in the struct because ARM stores the least
significant word at the lower address. On a big-endian
architecture, the fields would be reversed. This is why
[[FPdbleword]] lives in [[arm/u.h]] rather than the
portable headers.

%claude:
Recall that a double encodes the value $(-1)^S \times 1.M \times 2^{E-1023}$,
where $S$ is the sign bit, $E$ is the 11-bit exponent, and $M$ is
the 52-bit mantissa (the fractional part after an implicit
leading~1). The exponent is stored with a {bias} of 1023:
the actual exponent is $E - 1023$. The bias makes the
stored exponent always non-negative (an unsigned integer),
which simplifies hardware comparison---you can compare two
floats by comparing their bit patterns as integers.

For example:
\begin{verbatim}
  Value    S  Exponent (E)  Mantissa (M)   Meaning
  -----    -  ------------  ------------   -------
   1.0     0  01111111111   000...000      1.0 x 2^(1023-1023) = 1
  -1.0     1  01111111111   000...000      -(1.0 x 2^0) = -1
   0.5     0  01111111110   000...000      1.0 x 2^(1022-1023) = 0.5
   3.14    0  10000000000   100100011...   1.100100011... x 2^1 = 3.14
   NaN     0  11111111111   000...001      exp all 1s, mantissa != 0
  +Inf     0  11111111111   000...000      exp all 1s, mantissa = 0
\end{verbatim}
%
For 3.14: in binary $3.14 \approx 11.001000111\ldots$, which
normalizes to $1.1001000111\ldots \times 2^1$. The exponent
is $1 + 1023 = 1024$ (binary \verb+10000000000+), and the
mantissa stores \verb+1001000111...+ (the part after the
implicit leading~1).


\subsection{Strings and characters}

%http://reedbeta.com/blog/programmers-intro-to-unicode/

%yoann: small paragraph intro
%claude:
Text in C is represented at three levels: bytes (ASCII
characters), code points (Unicode characters), and encoded
byte sequences (UTF-8). Most C libraries blur these
distinctions, but \plan keeps them explicit: a [[char]] is
always a byte, a [[Rune]] is always a code point, and the
[[utf*]] functions handle the encoding between them.

\subsubsection{ASCII characters}

%claude:
Character classification uses a 256-entry lookup table
([<_ctype>]) where each byte is a bitmask of properties:
upper, lower, digit, space, punctuation, control. The
[[isalpha]], [[isdigit]], etc.\ macros index into this table,
making classification a single array lookup with no branches.

% type (unsigned) char

<<type [[Ctype_flag]]>>=
#define	_U	01 // upper
#define	_L	02 // lower
#define	_N	04 // number
#define	_S	010 // space
#define	_P	020 // punctuation
#define	_C	040 // ctlr
#define	_B	0100 // ??
#define	_X	0200 // valid hex digit
@


<<global [[_ctype]]>>=
uchar   _ctype[256] =
{
/*   0   1   2   3   4   5   6   7  */

/*  0*/ _C, _C, _C, _C, _C, _C, _C, _C,
/* 10*/ _C, _S|_C,  _S|_C,  _S|_C,  _S|_C,  _S|_C,  _C, _C,
/* 20*/ _C, _C, _C, _C, _C, _C, _C, _C,
/* 30*/ _C, _C, _C, _C, _C, _C, _C, _C,
/* 40*/ _S|_B,  _P, _P, _P, _P, _P, _P, _P,
/* 50*/ _P, _P, _P, _P, _P, _P, _P, _P,
/* 60*/ _N|_X,  _N|_X,  _N|_X,  _N|_X,  _N|_X,  _N|_X,  _N|_X,  _N|_X,
/* 70*/ _N|_X,  _N|_X,  _P, _P, _P, _P, _P, _P,
/*100*/ _P, _U|_X,  _U|_X,  _U|_X,  _U|_X,  _U|_X,  _U|_X,  _U,
/*110*/ _U, _U, _U, _U, _U, _U, _U, _U,
/*120*/ _U, _U, _U, _U, _U, _U, _U, _U,
/*130*/ _U, _U, _U, _P, _P, _P, _P, _P,
/*140*/ _P, _L|_X,  _L|_X,  _L|_X,  _L|_X,  _L|_X,  _L|_X,  _L,
/*150*/ _L, _L, _L, _L, _L, _L, _L, _L,
/*160*/ _L, _L, _L, _L, _L, _L, _L, _L,
/*170*/ _L, _L, _L, _P, _P, _P, _P, _C,
};
@

%yoann: maybe give example for charater 'A' which values it leads to
%claude:
For example, the character \verb+'A'+ has ASCII value 65.
To find it in the table above, note that the row/column
indices are in {\em octal}: 65 decimal is 101 octal, so
row \verb+/*100*/+ (octal 100 = decimal 64), column~1.
That entry is \verb+_U|_X+ (uppercase and hex digit).
This means [[isalpha('A')]] tests
\verb+(_U|_X) & (_U|_L)+, which is true because
the [[_U]] bit is set. [[isdigit('A')]] tests
\verb+(_U|_X) & _N+, which is false.

<<macros isxxx>>=
#define	isalpha(c)	(_ctype[(unsigned char)(c)]&(_U|_L))
#define	isupper(c)	(_ctype[(unsigned char)(c)]&_U)
#define	islower(c)	(_ctype[(unsigned char)(c)]&_L)
#define	isdigit(c)	(_ctype[(unsigned char)(c)]&_N)
#define	isxdigit(c)	(_ctype[(unsigned char)(c)]&_X)
#define	isspace(c)	(_ctype[(unsigned char)(c)]&_S)
#define	ispunct(c)	(_ctype[(unsigned char)(c)]&_P)
#define	isalnum(c)	(_ctype[(unsigned char)(c)]&(_U|_L|_N))
#define	isprint(c)	(_ctype[(unsigned char)(c)]&(_P|_U|_L|_N|_B))
#define	isgraph(c)	(_ctype[(unsigned char)(c)]&(_P|_U|_L|_N))
#define	iscntrl(c)	(_ctype[(unsigned char)(c)]&_C)
#define	isascii(c)	((unsigned char)(c)<=0177)
@


%claude:
The [[toupper]]/[[tolower]] functions take [[int]] rather than
[[char]]. In C, [[char]] is automatically promoted to [[int]]
when passed to a function, so these work transparently with
both [[char]] and [[Rune]] arguments. For
ASCII-range characters (below 128), the conversion is a simple
offset between the uppercase and lowercase ranges.

% ugly that take an int, because that way compatible with Rune??
<<function [[toupper]]>>=
int
toupper(int c)
{

    if(c < 'a' || c > 'z')
        return c;
    return _toupper(c);
}
@

<<macro [[_toupper]]>>=
#define	_toupper(c)	((c)-'a'+'A')
@

<<function [[tolower]]>>=
int
tolower(int c)
{

    if(c < 'A' || c > 'Z')
        return c;
    return _tolower(c);
}
@

<<macro [[_tolower]]>>=
#define	_tolower(c)	((c)-'A'+'a')
@


%yoann: explain what is the use of this macro?
%claude:
[[toascii()]] strips the high bit, forcing any byte into the
7-bit ASCII range (0--127). This is a blunt tool for
sanitizing input that might contain 8-bit characters, but
it destroys UTF-8 multi-byte sequences and is rarely useful
in \plan where UTF-8 is the native encoding.

<<macro [[toascii]]>>=
#define	toascii(c)	((c)&0177)
@

\subsubsection{Runes}

% aka code points in unicode terminology? 32 bits integers.
% or rune is already smaller?

% char =~ byte

%claude:
A [[Rune]] is \plan's name for a Unicode code point---a 21-bit
integer (stored in a 32-bit [[uint]]) that can represent any
character in the Unicode standard (up to U+10FFFF). The term ``rune''
was coined by Rob Pike and Ken Thompson when they designed
UTF-8 at Bell Labs. The name evokes the ancient Germanic
runes---symbols that carry meaning in a single glyph,
just as a [[Rune]] carries a single character regardless
of how many bytes it takes to encode.

%claude:
In \plan, [[char]] means a byte and
[[Rune]] means a character; the UTF-8 functions convert
between the two representations:
\begin{verbatim}
  Char   Rune (code point)   UTF-8 bytes      char[]
  ----   -----------------   -----------      ------
  A           U+0041 (65)       0x41            1 byte
  e-acute     U+00E9 (233)      0xC3 0xA9       2 bytes
  Greek beta  U+03B2 (946)      0xCE 0xB2       2 bytes
\end{verbatim}
%
The first example is plain ASCII---a single byte in all
representations. The second is the French letter \'e
(e with acute accent)---it looks similar to \verb+e+
but is a distinct Unicode character (code point 233,
above the ASCII range of 0--127), requiring 2~bytes
in UTF-8. The third is the Greek letter $\beta$, also
2~bytes. Characters from other scripts (Chinese, Japanese,
Arabic) require 3~bytes, and rare characters (emoji,
historic scripts) require 4.

<<type [[Rune]]>>=
typedef uint        Rune;
@

<<constant [[Runemax]]>>=
Runemax     = 0x10FFFF, /* 21-bit rune */
@
% see limit at https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Code_point

<<constant [[Runemask]]>>=
Runemask    = 0x1FFFFF, /* bits used by runes (see grep) */
@

\subsubsection{UTF8}

% utf(6)
% rune(2)

% typedef char* utf; ?

% diff with Rune? why we have some utfxxx and runexxx functions/?
% utf-8 is compact encoding of unicode characters (runes).

%claude:
UTF-8 is the variable-length encoding of runes into byte
sequences (1 to 4 bytes), designed by Ken Thompson and
Rob Pike. \plan was the first operating system with native
UTF-8 support throughout the entire system.
The encoding was designed under strict constraints:
backward compatibility with ASCII (so existing C programs
work unchanged), no null bytes inside multi-byte sequences
(so [[strlen]], [[strcpy]], etc.\ still work),
self-synchronization (from any byte position, you can find
the start of the current character by scanning for a byte
that does not begin with \verb+10+ in binary), and
byte-order matching code-point order (so [[strcmp]] on
UTF-8 strings gives the same ordering as comparing code
points directly).
%
The key constants are: [[UTFmax]] (4~bytes, the maximum
encoding length), [[Runeself]] (0x80, below which UTF-8 is
identical to ASCII), and [[Runeerror]] (the replacement
character for invalid sequences).

<<constant [[UTFmax]]>>=
UTFmax      = 4,        /* maximum bytes per rune */
@
<<constant [[Runesync]]>>=
Runesync    = 0x80,     /* cannot represent part of a UTF sequence (<) */
@
<<constant [[Runeself]]>>=
Runeself    = 0x80,     /* rune and UTF sequences are the same (<) */
@

<<constant [[Runeerror]]>>=
Runeerror   = 0xFFFD,   /* decoding error in UTF */
@

\section{Complex types}

%yoann: transition paragraph
%claude:
Beyond the scalar types above, the library defines a few
macros and typedefs related to pointers, arrays, structures,
and function calling conventions.

\subsection{Pointers}

%claude:
\plan uses [[nil]] instead of C's [[NULL]] because it is
shorter and, unlike [[NULL]], is always defined as
\verb+((void*)0)+---some C implementations define [[NULL]]
as plain \verb+0+, which can cause subtle bugs when passed
to variadic functions (where the compiler cannot infer that
an integer~0 should be a pointer).

<<constant [[nil]]>>=
#define nil     ((void*)0)
@
% why in u.h? could be in libc.h no?

%claude:
The [[uintptr]] type is an integer wide
enough to hold a pointer---critical for code that needs to
do arithmetic on addresses. You cannot do arbitrary arithmetic
on C pointers directly (e.g., masking the low bits for
alignment, or XOR-ing two pointers for a hash); you must
cast to [[uintptr]] first. For example, [[qsort]] checks
alignment with \verb!((uintptr)va + es) % sizeof(long)!
to decide whether to use word-sized or byte-sized swaps.

<<type [[uintptr]]>>=
typedef unsigned long   uintptr;
@
% tricky again when porting code! ptr size is different!

\subsection{Arrays (and [[qsort()]])}

%claude:
[[nelem()]] computes the number of elements in a statically
allocated array at compile time---a safer alternative to
hardcoding array sizes. 

<<function [[nelem]]>>=
#define nelem(x)    (sizeof(x)/sizeof((x)[0]))
@

%yoann: maybe show example of use of nelem() and show how better than alternative
%claude:
For example, given \verb+int table[16]+, writing
\verb+for(i=0; i<nelem(table); i++)+ is safer than
hardcoding \verb+i<16+---if the array size changes later,
[[nelem]] adapts automatically. Note that [[nelem]] only
works on actual arrays, not on pointers: if [[table]]
is passed to a function as \verb+int *table+, [[nelem]]
would give the wrong answer (the size of a pointer divided
by the size of an int).

%claude:
The [[qsort]] implementation uses quicksort. The naive
version picks the middle element as pivot, but that degrades
to $O(n^2)$ on certain inputs (e.g., already-sorted arrays).
This implementation uses a {\em median-of-three} pivot,
sampling at positions 1/6, 1/2, and 5/6 of the array and
choosing the median---a good approximation of the true
median that avoids worst-case behavior on common inputs.
After partitioning, it recurses on the smaller partition
and loops on the larger, which limits stack depth to
$O(\log n)$ even in the worst case.
%
Note also the two swap functions: [<swapi()>] swaps in
[[long]]-sized chunks (fast, for aligned data) and [<swapb()>]
swaps byte-by-byte (for unaligned data). [[qsort]] checks
alignment to choose between them.

<<type [[Sort]]>>=
typedef
struct
{
    int (*cmp)(void*, void*);
    void    (*swap)(char*, char*, long);
    long    es;
} Sort;
@

<<function [[qsort]]>>=
void
qsort(void *va, long n, long es, int (*cmp)(void*, void*))
{
    Sort s;

    s.cmp = cmp;
    s.es = es;
    s.swap = swapi;
    if(((uintptr)va | es) % sizeof(long))
        s.swap = swapb;
    qsorts((char*)va, n, &s);
}
@

<<function [[swapb]]>>=
static  void
swapb(char *i, char *j, long es)
{
    char c;

    do {
        c = *i;
        *i++ = *j;
        *j++ = c;
        es--;
    } while(es != 0);

}
@

<<function [[swapi]]>>=
static  void
swapi(char *ii, char *ij, long es)
{
    long *i, *j, c;

    i = (long*)ii;
    j = (long*)ij;
    do {
        c = *i;
        *i++ = *j;
        *j++ = c;
        es -= sizeof(long);
    } while(es != 0);
}
@

<<function [[pivot]]>>=
static  char*
pivot(char *a, long n, Sort *p)
{
    long j;
    char *pi, *pj, *pk;

    j = n/6 * p->es;
    pi = a + j; /* 1/6 */
    j += j;
    pj = pi + j;    /* 1/2 */
    pk = pj + j;    /* 5/6 */
    if(p->cmp(pi, pj) < 0) {
        if(p->cmp(pi, pk) < 0) {
            if(p->cmp(pj, pk) < 0)
                return pj;
            return pk;
        }
        return pi;
    }
    if(p->cmp(pj, pk) < 0) {
        if(p->cmp(pi, pk) < 0)
            return pi;
        return pk;
    }
    return pj;
}
@

<<function [[qsorts]]>>=
static  void
qsorts(char *a, long n, Sort *p)
{
    long j, es;
    char *pi, *pj, *pn;

    es = p->es;
    while(n > 1) {
        if(n > 10) {
            pi = pivot(a, n, p);
        } else
            pi = a + (n>>1)*es;

        p->swap(a, pi, es);
        pi = a;
        pn = a + n*es;
        pj = pn;
        for(;;) {
            do
                pi += es;
            while(pi < pn && p->cmp(pi, a) < 0);
            do
                pj -= es;
            while(pj > a && p->cmp(pj, a) > 0);
            if(pj < pi)
                break;
            p->swap(pi, pj, es);
        }
        p->swap(a, pj, es);
        j = (pj - a) / es;

        n = n-j-1;
        if(j >= n) {
            qsorts(a, j, p);
            a += (j+1)*es;
        } else {
            qsorts(a + (j+1)*es, n, p);
            n = j;
        }
    }
}
@


\subsection{Structures}

%claude:
[[offsetof()]] computes the byte offset of a field within a
structure at compile time. It works by casting [[nil]] to
a pointer to the structure and taking the address of the
field---the resulting address is the offset from zero.
This macro is used by container-of idioms: given a pointer
[[p]] to a [[next]] field inside a [[Free]] block, you can
recover the enclosing struct with
\verb+(Free*)((char*)p - offsetof(Free, next))+.
The Linux kernel uses the same pattern extensively via its
\verb+container_of+ macro.

<<function [[offsetof]]>>=
#define offsetof(s, m)  (ulong)(&(((s*)nil)->m))
@

\subsection{Functions}

%yoann: maybe recall need for va_list and va_xxx first; what is the problem they solve?
%claude:
C functions like [[print(char *fmt, ...)]] accept a variable
number of arguments. The problem is: how does the function
body retrieve those arguments? For a fixed-signature function,
the compiler generates code to read each parameter at a known
offset in the stack frame. But for variadic functions, the
compiler cannot generate this code because it does not know
how many arguments were passed. The
[[va_list]]/[[va_start]]/[[va_arg]]/[[va_end]] macros let
the function walk the stack frame at runtime, extracting
arguments one at a time.

%claude:
The [[va_start]] macro works by taking the address of the
last named parameter ([[&(start)]]) and pointing just past
it---this is where the first variadic argument lives on the
stack. So [[va_list]] is simply a [[char*]] pointer into
the stack:

\begin{verbatim}
  High addresses
  +----------+
  | arg N    |  <-- va_arg advances here
  +----------+
  | ...      |
  +----------+
  | arg 1    |  <-- va_start points here (after 'start')
  +----------+
  | start    |  <-- last named parameter
  +----------+
  Low addresses
\end{verbatim}
%
[[va_start]] sets the pointer just past the last named
parameter. Each call to [[va_arg]] reads the value at the
current position and advances the pointer by the argument's
size. Small types (1 or 2 bytes) are promoted to 4~bytes
on the stack, which the macros account for.

<<type [[va_list]]>>=
typedef char*   va_list;
@

<<macro [[va_start]]>>=
#define va_start(list, start) list =\
    (sizeof(start) < 4?\
        (char*)((int*)&(start)+1):\
        (char*)(&(start)+1))
@

<<macro [[va_end]]>>=
#define va_end(list)\
    USED(list)
@
<<macro [[va_arg]]>>=
#define va_arg(list, mode)\
    ((sizeof(mode) == 1)?\
        ((list += 4), (mode*)list)[-4]:\
    (sizeof(mode) == 2)?\
        ((list += 4), (mode*)list)[-2]:\
        ((list += sizeof(mode)), (mode*)list)[-1])
@

%yoann: example of use of all those macros together to illustrate and maybe ASCII diagram again
%claude:
Here is a complete example showing how these macros are used:
\begin{verbatim}
  int sum(int n, ...) {
      va_list ap;
      int i, total = 0;
      va_start(ap, n);       // ap points past n
      for(i = 0; i < n; i++)
          total += va_arg(ap, int);  // read and advance
      va_end(ap);
      return total;
  }
  // call: sum(3, 10, 20, 30) returns 60
\end{verbatim}
%
The call \verb+sum(3, 10, 20, 30)+ produces this stack:
\begin{verbatim}
  +------+
  | 30   |  <-- va_arg(ap, int) third time
  +------+
  | 20   |  <-- va_arg(ap, int) second time
  +------+
  | 10   |  <-- va_start(ap, n) points here
  +------+
  | 3    |  <-- n (last named parameter)
  +------+
\end{verbatim}
%
Each [[va_arg(ap, int)]] advances [[ap]] by 4~bytes (the
size of [[int]]) and returns the value at the previous
position. For a 1-byte [[char]], the macro still advances
by~4 (because of stack alignment) but reads from the correct
offset within the 4-byte slot.
%
In practice, passing an explicit count is unusual. Real
variadic functions use other conventions to know when to
stop: [[print]] uses the format string (each \verb+%+
verb implies one argument and its type), [[execl]] uses a
[[nil]] sentinel to mark the end of the argument list, and
[[EARGF]] in the argument parsing macros uses the structure
of command-line flags.

