\section{Time}
% Tm

%claude:
The [[Tm]] structure holds a broken-down time: year, month,
day, hour, minute, second, plus the timezone abbreviation
and offset from UTC. This is the same data that \unix's
[[struct tm]] holds, but with a better design: \plan puts
the timezone name ([[zone]]) and UTC offset ([[tzoff]])
directly inside the structure, whereas \unix splits them
into separate globals ([[tzname]], [[timezone]]) that are
not attached to any particular [[struct tm]]. The \plan
design means a [[Tm]] is self-contained---you can pass it
to another function without losing the timezone context.

%claude:
For example, March 25, 2026 at 14:30 in Rome would be
represented with [[hour]]=14, [[mon]]=2 (0-indexed),
[[year]]=126 (years since 1900), [[zone]]="CET",
and [[tzoff]]=3600 (one hour east of UTC).

<<type [[Tm]]>>=
struct Tm {
    int sec;
    int min;
    int hour;

    int mday;
    int mon;
    int year;
    int wday;
    int yday;

    char    zone[4];
    int     tzoff;
};
@
