\section{Normalizing a filename: [[cleanname()]]}

%real-world: realpath()

% cite \plan paper on dotdot?

%claude:
[[cleanname]] normalizes a file path in place: it removes
redundant slashes, eliminates \verb+.+ components, and
resolves \verb+..+ where possible. It also handles \plan's
\verb+#+ device syntax (e.g., \verb+#c/cons+) by preserving
the device prefix and treating the rest as a rooted path.
The two-pass approach first collapses duplicate slashes, then
processes dot-dot in a single forward scan---the [[d]] pointer
tracks the output position while [[s]] advances through the
input.

%claude:
Some worked examples, showing the rewrite as a series of
steps:
\begin{verbatim}
  Input               After dedup //   After ./..       Output
  -------------       --------------   --------------   --------
  /usr//rsc/.         /usr/rsc/.       /usr/rsc         /usr/rsc
  a/b/../c            a/b/../c         a/c              a/c
  /a/../../b          /a/../../b       /b               /b
  ../foo              ../foo           ../foo           ../foo
  ""                                                    .
  #c/cons             #c/cons          #c/cons          #c/cons
\end{verbatim}
%
Two cases are worth noticing. \verb+/a/../../b+ becomes
\verb+/b+: at the absolute root, an extra \verb+..+ is
swallowed (because \verb+/..+ equals \verb+/+ in
\plan---and in \unix---rather than being an error).
By contrast, \verb+../foo+ stays \verb+../foo+: a relative
path can keep leading \verb+..+ components, because there
is no way to know without consulting the filesystem how
many levels above the cwd the result actually lives. The
[[d0]] pointer is used to mark this: while [[d]] is still
sitting at [[d0]] and the path is not rooted, the
\verb+..+ branch advances [[d0]] past it instead of
deleting anything.

%claude:
This {lexical} resolution---working from the path string
alone, with no system calls---is what makes \plan
namespaces possible. Because [[..]] is resolved by
[[cleanname]] rather than by the filesystem, the parent of
\verb+/foo+ is always \verb+/+, even after
\verb+bind /home/x /foo+ has remapped \verb+/foo+ to
something completely different. \unix's
[[realpath()]] follows the filesystem's parent pointers
instead, which gives the wrong answer through bind mounts
and symbolic links and is one of the reasons \plan never
adopted symlinks.

<<macro [[SEP]]>>=
#define SEP(x)  ((x)=='/' || (x) == '\0')
@

% called also from kernel! in fixdotdotname
<<function [[cleanname]]>>=
/*
 * In place, rewrite name to compress multiple /, eliminate ., and process ..
 */
char*
cleanname(char *name)
{
    char *s;    /* source of copy */
    char *d;    /* destination of copy */
    char *d0;   /* start of path afer the root name */
    Rune r;
    bool rooted;

    if(name[0] == '\0')
        return strcpy(name, ".");

    rooted = false;
    d0 = name;
    if(d0[0] == '#'){
        if(d0[1] == '\0')
            return d0;
        d0  += 1 + chartorune(&r, d0+1); /* ignore slash: #/ */
        while(!SEP(*d0))
            d0 += chartorune(&r, d0);
        if(d0 == '\0')
            return name;
        d0++;   /* keep / after #<name> */
        rooted = true;
    }else if(d0[0] == '/'){
        rooted = true;
        d0++;
    }

    s = d0;
    if(rooted){
        /* skip extra '/' at root name */
        for(; *s == '/'; s++)
            ;
    }
    /* remove dup slashes */
    for(d = d0; *s != '\0'; s++){
        *d++ = *s;
        if(*s == '/')
            while(s[1] == '/')
                s++;
    }
    *d = '\0';

    d = d0;
    s = d0;
    while(*s != '\0'){
        if(s[0] == '.' && SEP(s[1])){
            if(s[1] == '\0')
                break;
            s+= 2;
            continue;
        }
        if(s[0] == '.' && s[1] == '.' && SEP(s[2])){
            if(d == d0){
                if(rooted){
                    /* /../x -> /x */
                    if(s[2] == '\0')
                        break;
                    s += 3;
                    continue;
                }else{
                    /* ../x -> ../x; and never collect ../ */
                    d0 += 3;
                }
            }
            if(d > d0){
                /* a/../x -> x */
                assert(d-2 >= d0 && d[-1] == '/');
                for(d -= 2; d > d0 && d[-1] != '/'; d--)
                        ;
                if(s[2] == '\0')
                    break;
                s += 3;
                continue;
            }
        }
        while(!SEP(*s))
            *d++ = *s++;
        if(*s == '\0')
            break;
        
        *d++ = *s++;
    }
    *d = '\0';
    if(d-1 > name && d[-1] == '/')  /* thanks to #/ */
        *--d = '\0';
    if(name[0] == '\0')
        strcpy(name, ".");
    return name;
}
@



\section{[[access()]]}

%claude:
[[access()]] checks file accessibility by actually trying to
open the file with the requested mode. For existence checks
([[AEXIST]]), it uses [<dirstat()>] instead. This is different
from \unix, where [[access()]] is a dedicated system call. The
\plan approach is more honest---it tests exactly what will
happen when you try to use the file---but it's also more
expensive, since it opens and immediately closes the file.

<<function [[access]]>>=
int
access(char *name, int mode)
{
    fdt fd;
    Dir *db;
    static char omode[] = {
        0,
        OEXEC,
        OWRITE,
        ORDWR,
        OREAD,
        OEXEC,  /* only approximate */
        ORDWR,
        ORDWR   /* only approximate */
    };

    if(mode == AEXIST){
        db = dirstat(name);
        free(db);
        if(db != nil)
            return 0;
        return -1;
    }
    fd = open(name, omode[mode&7]);
    if(fd >= 0){
        close(fd);
        return 0;
    }
    return -1;
}
@
